Missed places
1) tmp_fltn loads all history for DSID/environment

Here it should have been restricted to the prior active run, but it is not:

create or replace temporary table tmp_fltn as (
  select ...
  from DSE_TESTRESULTS p,
       lateral flatten(input => p.METRICRESULTS) f,
       lateral flatten(input => f.value) f1
  where p.dsid = :DSID
    and p.ENVIRONMENT_ID = :v_ENVIRONMENT_ID
);
Missing

RUNID = :v_MAX_RUNID

ACTV_IND = 'Y'

This is the biggest inconsistency because once TEMP_DSE_TESTRESULTS_STG is built from all runs, later joins can pick the wrong old row.

2) Metric-id reuse join DPR

This join uses all staged rows for the environment:

LEFT JOIN (
  Select distinct DSID, ENVIRONMENT_ID, MetricId, MetricName
  from TEMP_DSE_TESTRESULTS_STG
  where ENVIRONMENT_ID = :v_ENVIRONMENT_ID
) DPR
Missing

DSID = :DSID

RUNID = :v_MAX_RUNID

ACTV_IND = 'Y'

So metric ids can come from any staged historical row for that environment.

3) Max metric-id join DPR1

This one also uses all staged rows for the DSID/environment:

LEFT JOIN (
  Select distinct DSID, ENVIRONMENT_ID, max(MetricId) as metricId
  from TEMP_DSE_TESTRESULTS_STG
  where DSID = :DSID
    and ENVIRONMENT_ID = :v_ENVIRONMENT_ID
  group by DSID, ENVIRONMENT_ID
) DPR1
Missing

RUNID = :v_MAX_RUNID

ACTV_IND = 'Y'

So the max metric id can come from an older/inactive run too.

4) Prior result lookup lst

This one is close, but still incomplete:

select DSID, ENVIRONMENT_ID, metricId, metricName, result1, ...
from TEMP_DSE_TESTRESULTS_STG
where DSID = :DSID
  and Runid = :v_MAX_RUNID
  and ENVIRONMENT_ID = :v_ENVIRONMENT_ID
Missing

ACTV_IND = 'Y'

If same runid exists in stage with both active and inactive rows, this can still mix data.

5) “Lost metrics from prior run” logic

Outer query:

where R.DSID = :DSID
  and R.runid = (
      select max(runid)
      from TEMP_DSE_TESTRESULTS_STG
      where runid < :v_RunId
        and DSID = :DSID
        and ENVIRONMENT_ID = :v_ENVIRONMENT_ID
  )
  and R.metricId <> 0
  and R.ACTV_IND = 'Y'
  and R.ENVIRONMENT_ID = :v_ENVIRONMENT_ID
Missing in inner subquery

ACTV_IND = 'Y'

So the chosen prior runid comes from all staged rows, not only active prior rows.

Also, this block is using a different rule:

max(runid) < current runid

instead of the earlier:

v_MAX_RUNID from DSE_TESTRESULTS where ACTV_IND='Y'

That is another inconsistency.

6) “No prior history” check

This join checks only DSID/environment:

left outer join DSE_TestResults R
  on DPM.DSID = R.DSID
 and DPM.ENVIRONMENT_ID = R.ENVIRONMENT_ID
where R.DSID IS NULL
Missing

RUNID

ACTV_IND = 'Y'

This is not using the same prior-run identity either.

Not a read issue, but still inconsistent
7) Deactivate previous active rows

This update turns off all active rows for DSID/environment:

Update DSE_TESTRESULTS D1
Set D1.ACTV_IND = 'N'
WHERE D1.DSID = :DSID
  and ACTV_IND = 'Y'
  and D1.ENVIRONMENT_ID = :v_ENVIRONMENT_ID;
Missing

RUNID = :v_MAX_RUNID

This may be intentional, but it is not using the same key. If bad duplicate actives exist, it deactivates all of them.

Main conclusion

If you want the prior data to be consistently read as:

DSID = :DSID
AND ENVIRONMENT_ID = :v_ENVIRONMENT_ID
AND RUNID = :v_MAX_RUNID
AND ACTV_IND = 'Y'

then the code is currently missing that filter in these main places:

tmp_fltn

DPR

DPR1

lst in prior result update

inner subquery in lost-metrics logic

DSE_TestResults existence join

deactivate update if you want exact-row consistency there too

The most important fix

The safest pattern is:

create or replace temporary table TMP_PRIOR_RUN as
select *
from DSE_TESTRESULTS
where DSID = :DSID
  and ENVIRONMENT_ID = :v_ENVIRONMENT_ID
  and RUNID = :v_MAX_RUNID
  and ACTV_IND = 'Y';

Then use TMP_PRIOR_RUN everywhere old-run data is needed, instead of using all rows from DSE_TESTRESULTS / TEMP_DSE_TESTRESULTS_STG.

That removes most of the ambiguity immediately.
